[1
Date: 31 Aug 2000
From: Daniel Epstein <epsteind@paho.org>
Source: PAHO News Release on FMD

PAHO PROMOTES ACTIONS TO CONTROL FOOT-AND-MOUTH DISEASE IN COUNTRIES OF THE
SOUTHERN CONE
Official representatives of Bolivia, Brazil, Paraguay, and Uruguay [Note
that Argentina was not present. -Mod. PC have reported on the current
situation of Foot-and-mouth Disease in their territories, measures they
have taken, and actions being carried out in each country to prevent
further spread of the disease and protect the free areas. These measures
include declarations of states of alert, border controls, and restrictions
on beef imports, said Dr. Primo Arambulo, Coordinator of PAHO's Veterinary
Public Health Program.
In Montevideo, Uruguay, an emergency meeting of the members of the
Agreement of the River Plate basin for eradication of Foot-and-mouth
Disease was held yesterday, convened by the Pan American Health
Organization through its Pan American Foot-and-Mouth Disease Center
(PANAFTOSA), in response to requests by the countries facing the existing
emergency. Representatives of the private and official sectors of Bolivia,
Brazil, Paraguay, and Uruguay participated in the meeting, along with Chile
as an observer. At the meeting, participants emphasized the crucial
importance of maintaining in each country actions of surveillance,
diagnosis, and prevention, even in areas where eradication has been
achieved, with the human technical, and financial resources needed to
achieve the success of this objective, said Dr. Arambulo. Participants also
evaluated and approved the strategy implemented by Paraguay of vaccination
in the border area, given the levels of risk in that country.
Among the principal agreements, according to Dr. Arambulo, the members
ratified the need to use and strengthen existing mechanisms of
notification, coordination, and intercountry collaboration established in
the Agreement of the River Plate basin and other international groupings,
with technical cooperation from PANAFTOSA. The participants also agreed on
urgent operational actions aimed at auditing and evaluating in the field
the measures and actions applied by each country in areas affected by the
emergency, as well as the mobilization and allocation of necessary
financial resources for their execution. PAHO is supporting the countries
in developing and implementing a plan to eradicate Foot-and-Mouth Disease
from the Americas by the year 2007.
